entry.title: Milvus migrans
entry.content: These two, a whistling kite and a raven where doing acrobatics for about an hour in the morning with each other. Amazing to watch

entry.title: Microseris spp., Triodia scariosa
entry.content: A heap of Microseris coming up amongst the spinifex post burn.

entry.title: Arthropodium strictum s.l., Microlaena spp.
entry.content: This site has extreme grazing pressure from rabbits, wombats and kangaroos. Most plants are eaten unless hidden under logs or other hard to reach places.

entry.title: Australoplana alba/sanguinea alba, Australoplana spp.
entry.content: I think it is Australoplana sanguinea, but not sure. Found beneath a log amongst a Microlaena patch.

entry.title: Thinornis rubricollis
entry.content: Presumably nesting on the main surf beach (didn't want to get too close). There are leg bands on one of them, I sent a clearer photo to Birdlife for their records.

entry.title: Neosparassus diana
entry.content: Note the red mites on the spider

entry.title: Callocephalon fimbriatum
entry.content: Saw about 30 Gang-gang Cockatoos flying from the north to the south. Suprised to see so many this close to home away from large intact vegetation.
